42· This manly utterance was almost the last of the poet's life. A few scattered verses there may have been, closing per- haps with the touching appeal written from Verona (ci. ἕ 56) to his brother-poet, Cornificius, for a word of consolation, but that was all, and sometime in the year 54 rac, in his beloved Rome, so says the chronicler, the swiftly buming candle of his lise bumed itself out.

43. With him died the clearest, if not the richest, poet-voice ever lifted in Rome. He lacked the losty grandeur of Lucre· tius, the polished stateliness of Vergil, the broad sympathies of Horace. For on the one hand, he was no recluse to be filled with heavenly visions, and on the oth‘er, his personality was too intense to allow him to cultivate a tolerant spirit. He delighted in life with a vigorous animal passion. Not without charm to him was nature in her sylvan aspect (cf. eg. a. 34. 9 ff.) yet his highest enjoyment was in the life of men. And this lift he did not study, as did Horace, from the standpoint of a philosopher. Indeed, he did not study it at all, but simply felt it. = For he was not outside of it, but a part of it to the fullest degree, swayed by its ever-changing emotions. Such a nature must of necessity ever remain in many essential aspects the nature of a child. And such was the nature of Catullu throughout his brief lise,-warm in quiclr affectione, hot in swist hatreds, pulsing with most active red blood.
